We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties of the Municipality at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Continue to enjoin the GSO to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the Municipal Government;
Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the Municipal GSO;
Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee, and the Municipal Accountant to adhere to the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect reliable balances of PPE accounts.
Furthermore, we recommend that all issued property and equipment with a unit cost below the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00, that are still included in the PPE accounts, be appropriately derecognized from the PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004, dated May 31, 2022, and COA Circular No. 2024-006, dated March 14, 2024.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, and the concerned municipal employee to:
Observe the timely remittance of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee, as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid possible penalties;
Remit all taxes withheld, premium contributions, and loan repayment intact on or before the deadline as provided in the rules and regulations set by the BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid penalties, surcharges, and interests from delayed remittances;
Reconcile the Due to BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts with the actual amounts withheld based on the filed tax returns, statement of account, and loan amortization schedule from respective agencies, to identify the under- and over-remittances incurred from prior years until the current year; and
Encourage all employees to download and use GSIS, PAGIBIG, and PhilHealth apps on mobile devices to monitor personal contributions, claims, and loan payments.

14.6 	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive enforce the collection of these taxes, and:
require the Municipal Treasurer to exert more efforts to collect from the taxpayers and for those who have been unable to pay their taxes for several years, issue notices of delinquency for them to settle their unpaid taxes;
if circumstances warrant, avail of the Civil remedies provided for by the provisions of the Local Government Code (RA 7160), specifically Sections 174 to 176 thereof. Section 174 provides for the civil remedies which are by (a) administrative action through distraint of personal properties and (b) by judicial actions.  Section 175 provides for the procedure on the distraint of personal property and Section 176 provides for the levy of Real Properties.

25.5 	We recommended that management strictly adhere to the requirements of Section 2 of P.D. 1445 and direct the Engineering Department to:
Conduct inspection on the project site before the preparation of the POW in order to determine the soil texture and prepare POW accordingly, thus possible scaling and cracking of the PCCPs as well as falling down of riprap project will be avoided;
To closely monitor the implementation of municipal projects, thus possible improper works would be rectified if not avoided;
To reprimand contractors with unsatisfactory completed contracts from joining public bidding;
Blacklist those contractors who are causing damage to the municipality as a result of poorly completed projects.

28.9 	We recommended that the LCE:
28.9.1 	require the concerned implementing offices the prompt implementation of all projects/programs funded out of the tobacco excise tax in order to give the constituents, especially the tobacco farmers the early benefits that could be derived therefrom;
advise the Local Development Council and Municipal Accountant to determine the total unexpended balances of the completed and unimplemented projects and inform the LCE for possible reappropriation;
recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan to reappropriate for the priority project the funds saved from the fully implemented and the unimplemented projects which are no longer viable for implementation hence, funds could be used in accordance with the authorized uses as prescribed in RA Nos. 7171 and 8240.;
ensure that only feasible programs/projects/activities are included in the Annual Investment Program; and
require regular monitoring of implementation as basis in taking appropriate action.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties of the Municipality at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Enjoin the GSO to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the Municipal Government;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the GSO-Designate; and
Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set foth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect a more reliable balances of PPE accounts.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Initiate the reconstitution of the GFPS in accordance with Section 4.1.A.2 of PCW-DBM-DILG-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular 2013-01 for a comprehensive identification and response to GAD issues and concerns within the Municipality;
Immediately organize/constitute and strengthen a GAD Monitoring and Evaluation System through the issuance of an Executive Order pursuant to Section 5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 to enable the Municipality to assess the effectiveness and outcomes of its GAD policies, programs and projects;
Require the GAD M&E Team to conduct an evaluation of the outcomes of the LGU’s GAD policies, programs, and projects and submit a GAD Evaluation Report to the DILG Regional Office for the end of the three-year term in 2022 to serve as inputs to local policy-making and planning including GAD planning, programming, budgeting and implementation of the current administration;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer, in coordination with the LGU GFPS-TWG Chairman, to ensure strict adherence to the required 5% allocation for GAD-related activities on the LGU Annual Budget in line with Section 4.1.C.3 of the PCW-DBM-DILG-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular 2013-01; and
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer, in coordination with the LGU GFPS-TWG Chairman, to refrain from charging expenses that are not related in addressing gender-related issues. Furthermore, maintain an updated GAD Database to facilitate the identification of gender issues and ensure full implementation of the PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Stop the practice of reimbursing gasoline allowance to motor vehicles not owned by the LGU and/or privately owned;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant that the driver’s trip ticket shall be properly accomplished and serially numbered for control purposes and to submit Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumption and Official Travels to the Audit Team as required in COA Circular No. 77-61 to determine the reasonableness of fuel consumption.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and the concerned municipal employee to:
Observe the timely remittance of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth in order to avoid possible penalties;
Remit all taxes withheld, premium contributions, and loan repayment intact on or before the deadline as provided in the rules and regulations set by the BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid penalties, surcharges, and interests from delayed remittances;
Reconcile the Due to BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts with the actual amounts withheld based on the filed tax returns, statement of account, and loan amortization schedule from respective agencies, to identify the under and over-remittances incurred from prior years until the current year; and
Refund the unnecessary interest incurred, amounting to ₱11,451.19, due to delayed payment of PhilHealth contributions.

2.16. We recommended that Management:
a. Require MAO to maintain a separate SL for each fund transfer;
b. Ensure that future receipts of FA are covered with appropriate MOA specifically providing guidelines for project implementation and reporting;
c. Determine the projects that are fully implemented and return the excess to the respective SAs and proceed to submit the liquidation report to the SA; and
d. Take appropriate action for fund transfers whose stated purpose became no longer implementable/executable, either by returning them to the SA or obtaining similar approval from the appropriate government agency to ensure optimum utilization of the funds instead of holding them idle.

7.9. We reiterated the prior year’s recommendations that Management:
a. Require all concerned AOs to immediately settle their cash advances in accordance with the pertinent sections of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to monitor and strictly enforce the liquidation of cash advances within the prescribed period, and see to it that no additional cash advance shall be allowed unless the previous ones are settled or properly accounted for;
c. Ensure the settlement of outstanding cash advances of outgoing elected officials and employees before issuing their certificate of clearance; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular evaluation/ validation of all outstanding accounts; send demand letters to officers and employees with long outstanding accounts, and impose sanctions when necessary, such as withholding of their salaries as provided in the Circular; and, if warranted, request for a write-off of long-overdue cash advances following the procedures under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016

7.10. We recommended further that if the cash advance amount is less than the travel expenses incurred, a disbursement voucher should be prepared to liquidate the cash advance. This voucher will serve as a claim for reimbursement of the deficiency. Thus, the Municipal Accountant should credit the cash advance up to the amount initially disbursed.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Require the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) to formulate a COVID-19 Waste Management Plan and to incorporate the same in the Local Solid Waste Management Plan;

b. Request the MENRO to draft policies on: recognition of the threats posed by COVID-19 related health care wastes; and, the establishment of separate storage and collection bins for COVID-19 related health care wastes;

c. Direct the MENRO to conduct monitoring on each barangay to ensure that COVID-19 related health care wastes are segregated at the household level;

d. Request the Barangays under the Municipality to conduct an information drive to raise awareness of households on proper hygiene practices, and safe handling of infectious and contaminated health care wastes for collection; and,

e. Provide documentation on the segregation and storage activities for reference and archiving.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Require the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) and the Local Solid Waste Management Board to formulate policies on the collection and transport of COVID-19 related health care wastes;

b. Direct the MENRO to specify in the guidelines on waste management the important details on the collection and transport of COVID-19 related health care waste including, but not limited to the following: (a) manner of disinfection of collection and storage bins; (b) schedule of collection; (c) prohibition of manual segregation; and, (d) mandatory wearing of personal protective equipment for sanitation workers;

c. Instruct the Municipal Health Officer and the MENRO to conduct an orientation to waste collectors on the proper handling of COVID-19 related health care wastes; and,

d. Provide documentation on collection and transportation activities for reference and archiving.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following undertakings:

a. Direct the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) and Municipal Health Officer (MHO) to submit the microbial laboratory tests results of the treatment facility on COVID-19 related health care wastes to the DENR and/or DOH for approval;

b. Require the MENRO and MHO to conduct an orientation to waste disposal personnel on the classification of wastes being delivered for precautionary measures, maintaining a safe distance from, and avoid direct contact with the wastes;

c. Instruct the MENRO and Municipal Engineer to provide for the specifications and estimates in the construction of septic vaults for the treatment and disposal of domestic COVID-19 related health care wastes;

d. Require the MENRO to institute a recording mechanism that will monitor the treatment and disposal of COVID-19 related health care wastes; and,

e. Provide documentation on the activities related to the treatment and disposal activities for reference and archiving.

We recommended the following to the Municipal Mayor to efficiently and effectively manage the COVID-19 related health care wastes:

a. Establish a Composite Team in the Local Solid Waste Management Board (LSWMB) that will take charge in the development of policies pertaining to COVID-19 related health care wastes and for its implementation;

b. Require the MENRO and LSWMB to prepare a COVID-19 waste management plan and integrate the same to the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the Municipality;

c. Direct the MENRO to conduct orientation and other information drive about the proper management of COVID-19 related wastes in barangays;

d. Require the MENRO and the Composite Team to devise activities to support the Barangay Ecological Solid Waste Management Committees in the proper handling of COVID-19 related health care wastes in barangays.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Require the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENR) and the Municipal Health Officer (MHO) to prepare a specific Occupational Health and Safety Plan duly considering the risks faced by each department in the Municipality and to submit the same to the Office of the Municipal Mayor for approval and dissemination;

b. Require the MENRO and MHO to conduct: (a) orientation on the proper usage and maintenance of PPEs; and (b) trainings on Occupational Health and Safety with emphasis on the hazards in the workplace, environmental and administrative controls and the properties and characteristics of PPEs;

c. Direct the MENRO to provide disinfectants and hand sanitizers for every waste collection vehicle; and,

d. Provide documentation of activities on Occupational Health and Safety Plan implementation for reference and archiving.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Require the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) and the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) to prepare a database of Muslim families and communities in the Municipality through the assistance of the Barangays and to develop programs that will address their needs during the national health emergency;

b. Direct the MSWDO to keep abreast with the guidelines of regulatory agencies by attending conferences, visiting agency website and other activities that may be deemed appropriate.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Require the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) and the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) to prepare a list of persons with disabilities in the Municipality through the assistance of the Barangays and to develop programs that will address their needs during the national health emergency;

b. Direct the MSWDO to keep abreast with the guidelines of regulatory agencies by attending conferences, visiting agency website and other activities that may be deemed appropriate.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

a. Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) to reconcile their records to facilitate the computation of depreciation of PPE, and;

b. Require the MGSO to maintain Property Cards.

We recommended the following to the Municipal Mayor:

a. Require project and program proponents to ensure that proposals to be submitted to the Municipal Development Council are specific, measurable, attainable, realistic and time-bounded;

b. Direct members of the Municipal Development Council to: (a) establish parameters to be used in the appraisal and prioritization of programs and projects; and, (b) maintain an effective line of communication with the proponents and implementing offices to ensure that the planned programs and projects are implemented;

c. Direct the implementing offices to strictly observe the timelines set and should religiously coordinate with the Municipal Development Council in the execution of planned activities; and,

d. Instruct the Office of the Municipal Administrator to: (a) closely monitor the implementation of the projects; and, (b) devise a mechanism by which status of project implementation is reflected as a parameter in measuring individual performance of the concerned implementing offices and employees.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:

Direct the GAD Technical Working Group (TWG) to formulate and adopt programs that will protect, promote and support breastfeeding of infants or young children program in the Municipality through the establishment of breastfeeding facilities and the promotion of breastfeeding through information dissemination;

Communicate planned policies with the Sangguniang Bayan for the formulation of an ordinance that: (a) recognizes the importance of breastfeeding in the development of the society; and, (b) lays out the policies that protects, promotes and supports breastfeeding.

We recommended that the Acting Municipal Mayor direct the:
a) Inventory Committee to –
• prepare and submit the PIP for approval of the Municipal Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory is properly and adequately planned;
• submit a copy of the approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled inventory taking activities;
• complete the conduct of physical count of all PPE at least once a year and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) classified per category/type to the Office of the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and
• follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of inventory prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006.
b) MGSO to update the PCs based on the result of the physical inventory and maintain them per category and with complete information about the PPE;
c) Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELCs for individual property items complete with details of the PPE; and
d) MGSO and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the balances of their respective records of PPE.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:
15. Direct the GAD Technical Working Group (TWG) to formulate and adopt programs that will protect, promote and support breastfeeding of infants or young children program in the Municipality through the establishment of breastfeeding facilities and the promotion of breastfeeding through information dissemination;
16. Communicate planned policies with the Sangguniang Bayan for the formulation of an ordinance that: (a) recognizes the importance of breastfeeding in the development of the society; and, (b) lays out the policies that protects, promotes and supports breastfeeding.

We recommended that the LCE 

(a) require the Municipal Treasurer,  also the General Services Officer, to  prioritize the conduct of physical inventory of PPE and reconcile the results thereof with the accounting records; 

(b) require the Accounting Office and Treasury Office/GSO to maintain the appropriate property records such as PPELC and PLC, respectively, and provide the necessary allowance for depreciation on all depreciable assets of the Municipality; 

(c) instruct the Municipal officials concerned to exert effort to facilitate the transfer of the title of the purchased parcel of land in the name of the Municipality, the soonest possible time; and 

(d) immediately facilitate the disposal of unserviceable property to prevent further loss and deterioration.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor 

(a) direct the concerned officials to observe strictly the general guidelines on the information and publicity of projects undertaken by the Municipality in accordance with the COA Circular No. 2013-004  dated January 30, 2013; 

(b) require the  Municipal Engineer to (i) ensure that the infrastructure projects conform with the documentary requirements provided by the DPWH Standard Specifications for Highways, Bridges and Airport; (ii) require the contractors to  repair the defective and damaged portion of the road projects pursuant to the one year warranty period  from the date of project completion up to final acceptance or the defects liability period pursuant to Section 62 of the CY 2016 IRR of RA No. 9184; 

(c) require the Municipal Planning Officer and the Municipal Engineer to implement and monitor regularly the status of all implemented projects as embodied in their local development plan; and 

(d) require the Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of the documentary requirements for infrastructure projects prior to payment.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the MENRO
 (a) involve closely the Barangay officials in solid waste management and activate the Solid Waste Management Committees in every Barangay for the strict enforcement and continuous implementation of the existing environmental laws especially on establishment of MRF and waste segregation at source; 
(b) intensify information campaign on solid waste management and educate the constituents on the necessity of   the construction of MRF in every Barangay and establishing programs on composting, recycling, re-use, and recovery of solid waste generated; 
(c) consider extending financial assistance, resources, and technology to all of the three Barangays which  remained non-compliant to the basic requirements of R.A. No. 9003; and  
(d) develop programs on  composting, recycling, re-use, and recovery of solid waste generated in order to reduce hauling and disposal costs of the Municipality.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
1. Issue the appropriate demand letters to the persons responsible for the unauthorized disbursement;
2. Prepare the necessary adjusting entries thereof.

